the Salem witchcraft panic and the Spanish Inquisition in New Mexico; as indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland; caught up between warring British and Native Americans; as traders in New Netherlands and Detroit; as slave owners in Jamaica; as Loyalist women during the American Revolution; enslaved in the President's house; and as students and educators inspired by the air of equality in the young nation.Foster showcases the latest research of junior and senior historians, drawing from recent scholarship informed by women's and gender history-feminist theory, gender theory, new cultural history, social history, and literary criticism. Collectively, these essays address the need for scholarship on women's lives and experiences. Women in Early America heeds the call of feminist scholars to not merely reproduce male-centered narratives, "add women, and stir," but to rethink master narratives themselves so that we may better understand how women and men created and developed our historical past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aWomenxHistoryx17th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aBerkin, Carol1 aFoster, Thomas A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorgan, Jennifer L.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479876419.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBAC